1 SECTION 4. Lower Income Threshold for Sales Tax Exemption. –
2 G.S. 105-164.13E reads as rewritten:
3 "§ 105-164.13E. Exemption for farmers.
4 (a) Exemption. – A qualifying farmer is a person who has either (i) an annual income
5 from farming operations for the preceding taxable year of ten thousand dollars ($10,000) or more
6 or who has seven thousand five hundred dollars ($7,500) or more or (ii) an average annual income
7 from farming operations for the three preceding taxable years of ten thousand dollars ($10,000)
8 seven thousand five hundred dollars ($7,500) or more. For purposes of this section, the term
9 "income from farming operations" means sales plus any other amounts treated as gross income
10 under the Code from farming operations. A qualifying farmer includes a dairy operator, a poultry
11 farmer, an egg producer, and a livestock farmer, a farmer of crops, a farmer of an aquatic species,
12 as defined in G.S. 106-758, and a person who boards horses. A qualifying farmer may apply to
13 the Secretary for an exemption certificate number under G.S. 105-164.28A. The exemption
14 certificate expires when a person fails to meet the income threshold for three consecutive taxable
15 years or ceases to engage in farming operations, whichever comes first.
16 Except as otherwise provided in this section, the items exempt under this section must be
17 purchased by a qualifying farmer or conditional farmer and used by the qualifying or conditional
18 farmer primarily in farming operations. For purposes of this section, an item is used by a farmer
19 for farming operations if it is used for the planting, cultivating, harvesting, or curing of farm
20 crops, in the production of dairy products, eggs, or animals, or by a person who boards horses.
21 The items that may be exempt from sales and use tax under this section are:
22 …
23 (b) Conditional Exemption. – A person who does not meet the definition of a qualifying
24 farmer in subsection (a) of this section may apply to the Department for a conditional exemption
25 certificate under G.S. 105-164.28A. A person with a conditional exemption certificate is allowed
26 to purchase items exempt from sales and use tax to the same extent as a qualifying farmer under
27 subsection (a) of this section. To receive a conditional exemption certificate under this
28 subsection, the person must certify that the person intends to engage in farming operations, as
29 that term is described in subsection (a) of this section, and that the person will timely file State
30 and federal income tax returns that reflect income and expenses incurred from farming operations
31 during the taxable years that the conditional exemption certificate applies.
32 A conditional exemption certificate issued under this subsection is valid for the taxable year
33 in which the certificate is issued and the following two taxable years, provided the person to
34 whom the certificate is issued is engaged in farming and provides copies of applicable State and
35 federal income tax returns to the Department within 90 days following the due date of an income
36 tax return for each taxable year covered by the conditional exemption certificate, including an
37 extension of the due date granted by the Secretary under G.S. 105-263. A conditional exemption
38 certificate issued under this subsection may not be extended or renewed beyond the original
39 three-year period; provided that a person may request a one-year extension of their conditional
40 exemption certificate if the person satisfies all of the following conditions:
41 …
42 (3) The person provides the Department all of the following:
43 a. Documents showing that, but for the disaster, the person would have
44 earned ten thousand dollars ($10,000) seven thousand five hundred
45 dollars ($7,500) or more in gross sales for the year in which the
46 disaster occurred.
47 …."
48 SECTION 5. This act becomes effective July 1, 2025. Section 4 of this act applies
49 to exemption certificates issued on or after that date.
